CELEBRATIONS to mark the late President Nelson Mandela’s centenary kicked off smoothly at the weekend with the first event starting in Mthatha. Mandela would have turned 100 on 18 July this year.The event was hosted by the Nelson Mandela Museum. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Family, officials and ordinary people shared fond memories of the late Tata Madiba under the theme “Release Mandela Historic Memories” marking 28 years since his release from prison.Some of the surviving members of Mandela’s Welcome Reception Committee, like Dali Mpofu, Rose Sonto, Saki Macozoma and Hilda Ndude, spoke of unknown stories surrounding the release of Mandela on 11 February 1990.Sonto, who drove Mandela out of Victor Verster Prison in Cape Town, said he had shivered when he finally realised that he was driving Mandela. “My knees went weak at the thought that I was tasked to carry cargo that was more precious than gold,” he said.They also told of how Madiba did not want to leave prison without his then wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, besides him.The Nelson Mandela Foundation said: “While we commemorate 2018 as the centenary of the birth of this great South African, Madiba has left us with rich layers of milestones in his remarkable life.” Mandla Mandela urged ANC president Cyril Ramaphosa to use the celebrations to strengthen the call for the freedom of Palestinian prisoners in Israel.